## Weather Event Transportation Protocol Differences

Colorado weather creates transportation scenarios during sports events that reveal how different services adapt to challenging conditions. Snow games, rain events, and high wind conditions each require different transportation approaches that affect service reliability and availability.

Snow event protocols require transportation services to switch to winter-configured vehicles with appropriate tires, chains, and equipment. This vehicle changeover reduces overall capacity because not all fleet vehicles meet winter operation requirements. Services prioritize safety over capacity, which extends wait times but ensures operational capability.

Rain event complications center around covered pickup areas that become bottlenecks when everyone seeks shelter. Transportation coordination must account for concentrated demand in limited covered areas while most pickup zones become less desirable. Vehicle loading takes longer in rain conditions due to safety precautions and passenger comfort considerations.

High wind conditions affect vehicle stability and safety, particularly for larger passenger vehicles. Transportation services may suspend certain vehicle types during high wind events, reducing capacity and changing service availability. Emergency protocols during wind events include coordination with venue security for passenger safety during boarding.

Temperature extremes create different challenges for transportation coordination. Extreme cold requires vehicle preheating and extended boarding times for passengers with mobility limitations. Extreme heat creates similar extended boarding requirements plus considerations for medical conditions that may be affected by temperature exposure.

